<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1855,2024]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,432]" lastPageId="8" pageId="7">
We have several more specimens on hand which belong to at least three more species that also have a triangular pterostigma. All these specimens have an elevated transverse ridge on the frons above the two white pubescent spots next to the eye margin and the antennae are not inserted on the protrusion as in 
<emphasis box="[1226,1370,1927,1952]" italics="true" pageId="7">
<taxonomicName box="[1226,1365,1927,1952]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Psapharomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salebrosa">P. salebrosa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Also, the flange between the oral cavity and the lower eye margin is not triangular as in 
<taxonomicName box="[1107,1244,1963,1988]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Psapharomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salebrosa">
<emphasis box="[1107,1244,1963,1988]" italics="true" pageId="7">P. salebrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but varies from evenly curved and barely visible to a large but not triangular flange. One of the specimens has the eyes covered with setae. We still believe that these species would be best placed in this genus which is mainly defined by the triangular shaped pterostigma.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,432]" pageId="8">
This genus is part of a group of African genera which are defined by having vein 
<emphasis box="[1189,1206,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="8">R</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[1206,1231,238,252]" italics="true" pageId="8">2+3</emphasis>
arising distinctly proximal to crossvein 
<emphasis box="[411,456,264,287]" italics="true" pageId="8">r–m</emphasis>
, abdomen longer than broad, head of females longer than high, male eyes holoptic; pedicel with a finger-like projection on the inner side (similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[901,1004,300,323]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Ptecticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[901,1004,300,323]" italics="true" pageId="8">Ptecticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The following genera belong in the 
<emphasis box="[151,320,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="8">Steleoceromys-</emphasis>
group: 
<taxonomicName authority="Lindner, 1965" authorityName="Lindner" authorityYear="1965" box="[423,783,334,359]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Dactylotinda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[423,570,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="8">Dactylotinda</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lindner" box="[600,783,334,359]" pageId="8" refString="Lindner, E. (1965) Stratiomyiidae (Diptera Brachycera). Parc National de la Garamba. - Mission H. De Saeger en collaboration avec P. Baert, G. Demoulin, I. Denisoff, J. Martin, M. Micha, A. Noirfalise, P. Schoemaker, G. Troupin et J. Verschuren (1949 - 1952), 46, 45 - 65." type="journal article" year="1965">Lindner, 1965</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[818,971,336,359]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hypoceromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[818,971,336,359]" italics="true" pageId="8">Hypoceromys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[1008,1365,334,359]" italics="true" pageId="8">
<taxonomicName box="[1008,1162,334,359]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Psapharomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Psapharomys</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1196,1361,334,359]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Pseudoxymyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pseudoxymyia</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[151,318,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="8">
<taxonomicName box="[151,314,370,395]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Steleoceromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Steleoceromys</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Further studies are needed to better define the genera and to resolve the phylogenetic relationships among the genera. Unfortunately most of these species are rather rare in collection.
</paragraph>
